speaking from experience, you just keep pushing through until you write enough that you're satisfied for the day/week
if you're having trouble focusing on writing, turn off any and all distractions, including this shithole of a thread
just write, keep writing until you find a good stopping point for the day, then spend a little time going over what you did, correct any mistakes, etc
9 times out of 10, this helps me actually get some writing done for the day
then again, I haven't updated in a month, so take what I say with a grain of salt

Anonymous Wed 15 May 2019 18:55:27 No.23137608 Report
Quoted By: >>23138110
>>23137193

>>23137268
Is good advice, regardless if he is in a slump or not.
Pacing is something that i struggle with too. There is nothing wrong with just writing a quick blurb to push to the more interesting part you want to get to, then going back and rewriting and fixing stuff
One line i think of over and over again is “is this the most interesting point in the protagonist’s story? If not, why are we here for this part?” That, and you need to accept you are not Shakespeare. None of us are. We are novice to semi novice writers that make mistakes, write garbage, and just bullshit our way to make something that satisfies us and our audience. It’s no real excuse to just sweep everything under the rug, never truly settle for something basic, but try to have more fun and just enjoy it. This is your hobby, not your job, so make mistakes and fix them later without worry. And honestly? >>23137268 makes a good point of ignoring the thread as a whole. Half of the time it ends up being a turnoff for writing.
